WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.920
Do you have to look at the docs every time you make a plot in Python?

00:00:03.920 --> 00:00:07.760
Using a precise grammar helps you build and describe plots.

00:00:07.760 --> 00:00:11.200
There's a whole book about the grammar of graphics itself,

00:00:11.200 --> 00:00:14.160
but the theory is basically that you layer…

00:00:14.160 --> 00:00:15.200
Data

00:00:15.200 --> 00:00:16.480
Aesthetics

00:00:16.480 --> 00:00:17.280
Geoms

00:00:17.280 --> 00:00:18.160
Facets

00:00:18.160 --> 00:00:19.360
Statistics

00:00:19.360 --> 00:00:20.080
Coordinates

00:00:20.080 --> 00:00:20.559
Themes

00:00:21.840 --> 00:00:25.840
You can use a grammar of graphics in Python with the plotnine package.

00:00:26.639 --> 00:00:32.480
This grammar allows you to make and describe any plot, no matter what it looks like.

00:00:34.639 --> 00:00:36.400
Start by loading in your data.

00:00:39.919 --> 00:00:42.639
Add your data to your grammar of graphics plot.

00:00:46.080 --> 00:00:50.080
Next, add your aesthetics, like x and y variables.

00:00:50.080 --> 00:00:56.320
Then, add geom shapes such as points. These will be applied to your aesthetics.

